As the original poster said, this is tough being that the entire class is static.  Even with this change you would have no way to alter the format of the outputted date unless you call one of the toJson(Date) methods.

```
toJson([a:'foo', b: new Date()]) // will use default, no way to alter format or tz
```

One alternative may be to return to using a `ThreadLocal` (just not a sub-class that would cause leaks in Tomcat per [GROOVY-7143](https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GROOVY-7143)) and check a system property to determine if ISO8601 dates should be outputted.

``` groovy
.....
.....
    private static final String DATE_FORMAT_KEY = "groovy.json.JsonOutput.dateFormat";
    private static final String DATE_FORMAT_VAL_ISO8601 = "ISO8601";
    private static final String JSON_DATE_FORMAT_ISO8601 = "yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ssXX";
    private static final String DEFAULT_TIMEZONE_ISO8601 = "UTC";

    private static final ThreadLocal<DateFormat> dateFormatter = new ThreadLocal<DateFormat>() {
        @Override
        protected DateFormat initialValue() {
            SimpleDateFormat df = null;
            if (DATE_FORMAT_VAL_ISO8601.equals(System.getProperty(DATE_FORMAT_KEY))) {
                df = new SimpleDateFormat(JSON_DATE_FORMAT_ISO8601, Locale.US);
                df.setTimeZone(TimeZone.getTimeZone(DEFAULT_TIMEZONE_ISO8601));
            } else {
                df = new SimpleDateFormat(JSON_DATE_FORMAT, Locale.US);
                df.setTimeZone(TimeZone.getTimeZone(DEFAULT_TIMEZONE));
            }
            return df;
        }
    };
.....
.....
.....
    /**
     * Serializes date and writes it into specified buffer.
     */
    private static void writeDate(Date date, CharBuf buffer) {
        buffer.addQuoted(dateFormatter.get().format(date));
    }
.....
.....
```

Then calling code could turn on ISO8601 dates

``` groovy
    // From command line:
    //     groovy -Dgroovy.json.JsonOutput.dateFormat=ISO8601 myscript.groovy
    // or from code
    System.setProperty("groovy.json.JsonOutput.dateFormat", "ISO8601");
    JsonOutput.toJson([a:'foo', b: d]) //== {"a":"foo","b":"2008-03-04T12:50:00Z"}
```

You could provide a setter in addition to or in place of the System Property and update the thread local variable.

``` groovy
    public static void setDateFormat(DateFormat dateFormat) {
        dateFormatter.set(dateFormat);
    }
```

This gets around the thread safety issue.  However, it's probably not uncommon to have multiple threads processing JSON payloads concurrently.  With having a static setter any changes affect all threads which may be surprising and with thread local you have to remember to call the setter from each thread which may also be surprising.

Hi - I'm the IBM engineer who has been discussing this with @candrews 

Below is a testcase which I've been investigating.  Running this on Groovy 2.4.5 with IBM's implementation of Java SE 8 shows a memory leak (with -Xmx256m it throws `OutOfMemoryError` in a few minutes).  If I add the system property `-Dgroovy.use.classvalue=true` the memory leak is fixed and the testcase runs indefinitely with no problems.

I think this shows that the `java.lang.ClassValue` code @candrews added for Java 7+ works as designed on IBM's runtime.

Test.java:

``` java
package demo;

import groovy.lang.GroovyShell;

public class Test {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {

            new Thread(new Runnable() {

                @Override
                public void run() {

                    long i = 0;
                    while (true) {
                        new GroovyShell().evaluate(i + " * 2", "Script_" + i);
                        i++;

                    }
                }

            }).start();
        }

        while (true);
    }
}
```
